Regal Mall of Georgia Stadium 20 & IMAX

fields.notes: So exhilarating that I can barely even bring myself to note the two biggest holes in the plot.

Though he is visibly giving everything he has to it, Cruise -- at this stage in his career already a supremely charismatic and incredibly skilled physical performer -- just doesn't yet have the emotional or dramatic chops for the role. But even more importantly it mainly suffers from typical biopic problems. Stone and Kovic's ham-fisted script has a couple of terrific sequences (the VA hospital, the stretch in Mexico), but pretty much bungles the rest in an effort to cover too much ground and/or make sure you never go a moment without getting its (already self-evident) message. Also, what a growth spurt Ron has there at the beginning, huh? To go from looking like he's 12 while watching Kennedy's inaugural address in January 1961 to being an 18-year-old high school graduate in 1964. Jesus, Oliver, cast another kid or put Cruise there. Something.
